📊 Data Handling
Automated Employee Onboarding & Offboarding System
1. Overview

Data handling in an onboarding/offboarding system ensures that employee information is collected, processed, stored, accessed, and deleted securely and consistently throughout the employee lifecycle.

It covers HR data, IT access data, documents, logs, and system-generated workflow data.

2. Types of Data Managed
2.1 Employee Master Data

Core HR information:

Employee ID
Name, DOB, contact details
Department, designation
Reporting manager
Employment status (Active / Exited)
2.2 Identity & Access Data

Used for system access control:

Email accounts
System usernames
Role-based permissions
Login activity logs
MFA settings
2.3 Workflow Data

Generated by onboarding/offboarding processes:

Task assignments
Approval records
Workflow status
SLA timestamps
2.4 Document Data

Sensitive HR documents:

Offer letters
Contracts & NDAs
Policy acknowledgments
Exit forms
2.5 Audit & Log Data

System tracking data:

Access logs
Admin actions
Data modification history
Security events
3. Data Lifecycle Management
3.1 Data Collection
Collected from HR systems or onboarding forms
Validated at entry point
Mandatory fields enforced (e.g., employee ID, email)
3.2 Data Processing
Workflow engine uses employee data to trigger tasks
Role mapping determines system access
HR updates propagate to IT systems automatically
3.3 Data Storage
Stored in centralized database (encrypted)
Separated into structured and document storage
Backed up regularly (daily/weekly schedules)
3.4 Data Usage

Used for:

Account creation and access provisioning
Payroll and compliance processes
Reporting and analytics
Audit and governance
3.5 Data Archival

When employee exits:

Active data is moved to archive storage
Access is restricted to authorized roles only
Retention rules are applied
3.6 Data Deletion
Executed after retention period expires
Secure deletion (not soft delete)
Ensures no recovery from production systems
Documented for compliance audits
4. Data Security Controls
4.1 Access Control
Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)
Least privilege principle
Temporary access with expiration
4.2 Encryption
Data in transit: TLS/HTTPS
Data at rest: AES-256 encryption
Secure key management system
4.3 Authentication
Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) for admins
Single Sign-On (SSO) for employees
Session timeout policies
4.4 Audit Logging
All critical actions logged
Immutable log storage (write-once)
Regular audit reviews
5. Data Retention Policy
Data Type	Retention Period
Employee Master Data	As per employment + 5–7 years
Access Logs	6–12 months
Documents (HR/legal)	5–10 years (compliance-based)
Workflow Logs	1–2 years
Archived Employee Data	As per legal requirement
6. Data Privacy & Compliance

The system should comply with:

Data minimization principles
Purpose limitation (data used only for HR operations)
Consent-based processing where required
Regional privacy regulations (e.g., GDPR-like policies if applicable)
7. Data Flow Summary
Onboarding Flow:

HR Input → Validation → Workflow Engine → IAM System → IT Tools → Audit Logs

Offboarding Flow:

Exit Trigger → Access Revocation → Asset Tracking → Archival → Secure Deletion (after retention period)

8. Data Backup & Recovery
Daily incremental backups
Weekly full backups
Disaster recovery environment
Recovery testing quarterly
Point-in-time restoration capability
9. Data Quality Management
Duplicate employee detection
Mandatory field validation
Periodic data cleanup
Sync validation across systems
10. Exception Handling
Issue	Handling Method
Missing employee data	Block workflow initiation
Sync failure	Retry + alert admin
Access mismatch	Auto-correction or ticket generation
Corrupt records	Restore from backup
